1. What is the goal of deregression?

Deregressed breeding values (DRP) are designed to strip off the contribution of the parental average (PA) from an individualâ€™s estimated breeding value (EBV), leaving a value that represents the individualâ€™s own genetic information (i.e., the Mendelian sampling term), untainted by the information that came via ancestors.

This is crucial because if you donâ€™t remove the PA properly, and you use these values in a second genetic evaluation (like genomic prediction), you risk double-counting ancestral information.

