2. Why PEV of the Mendelian sampling effect matters?

The Mendelian sampling term (MS) is the deviation of an animalâ€™s breeding value from its PA:

MS = EBV - PA

However, this MS is estimated with error in the genetic evaluation model â€” it is not a perfect measure because data is limited.

The prediction error variance (PEV) associated with the MS effect quantifies how uncertain this estimation is. In Garrickâ€™s formula, this error variance is essential for determining how much weight the deregressed value should have in subsequent analyses.

